@@ -6,6 +6,8 @@ Convention adopted 2026-05-08 after the AEP-Plugin PR review surfaced confusion
 
 ## 2026-07-17
 
+- [x] **task_024: hunk-aware diff parsing — close the added-line header-spoof hole in the content scanner** — both diff parsers in `vibe-content-scan.sh` trusted line SHAPE to classify diff-stream lines, but diff content is attacker-controlled: an ADDED line whose content begins `++ ` renders with its `+` prefix as `+++ …` and was misparsed as a file header. In `scan_diff_stream` (`--staged`/`--range`) a crafted `++ /dev/null` added line rendered `+++ /dev/null` and set `skip_file=1`, silently skipping EVERY finding — including BLOCK secrets — for the rest of that file's hunks (pre-existing, task_019); `++ b/<path>` similarly flipped `current_file`/`current_file_tier` (WARN-demotion variant, task_023 review INFO). In `scan_blob_stdin` (`vibe audit --history` pass 1) the same shape was dropped as header noise, so a secret on a line beginning `++ ` was never scanned. Fix: parse the `@@ -a[,c] +b[,d] @@` hunk headers' line COUNTS — which git generates and content cannot forge (every in-hunk line carries a `+`/`-`/space/`\` prefix). On each real hunk header the parser records `old_remaining=<c>` (default 1 when omitted, `,0` legal) and `new_remaining=<d>`; while `old_remaining+new_remaining>0` it is INSIDE the hunk and classifies purely by first byte — `-` decrements old; `+` decrements new AND is scanned as content (exactly one `+` stripped, even if the content starts `++ `/`@@ `); a leading space (U3 context) decrements BOTH; a ZERO-BYTE empty line is a `diff.suppressBlankEmpty=true` context line (checked BEFORE prefix classification) and decrements BOTH; a leading `\` (`\ No newline…`) decrements nothing and is not scanned. Header classification (`+++ `, `commit `, `@@ `) applies ONLY when both counters are zero. A malformed `@@` whose counts don't parse fails SAFE (treated as not-a-header; counters stay zero; scanning continues under the prior state) — never a `set -e` crash, never a wedged unbounded "inside" state; EOF mid-hunk is tolerated. `scan_blob_stdin`'s outside-hunk branch still scans bare `+`-prefixed lines as content, so degenerate header-less streams (the frozen task_022 corpus) stay byte-identical, while real `git log -p` — where every added line sits inside a hunk — routes spoof-shaped lines through the inside-hunk path. Deliberate, narrow behaviour change: spoof-shaped added lines are now scanned as content (a secret behind a `++ ` prefix is caught in every diff-based mode) and forged headers no longer flip file/tier/skip state; the forged-budget vector (an added line beginning `@@ …` renders `+@@ …`, so hostile content can never case-match a real hunk header and re-arm the counters) is provably closed and pinned by a permanent fixture. All other lines behave byte-identically to the pre-task_024 parser: proven by differential vs the pinned baseline sha over the full 92k-line `git log -p --all` history — a SINGLE new finding across all history (one WARN home-path), mechanically traceable to a `+++ `-prefixed added line the old parser dropped as header noise, and ZERO new BLOCK findings (the audit's pre-existing 57 history BLOCK fixtures and its exit code are unchanged). Per-hunk count parsing is builtin-only (`[[ =~ ]]` + `BASH_REMATCH`, POSIX ERE held in a variable, no fork on the per-line path — task_022's no-fork/no-word-boundary-escape/no-bash-4 static shape guards stay green), bash 3.2 + nounset safe (no arrays introduced; decrements guarded via the existing `[ … ] && …` idiom). Verified via a scratch fixture-corpus harness (not committed — gitignored under `.vs/cycle-*/`) building real git repos + hand-built streams: AC1 (`++ /dev/null` skip-state spoof, staged + range), AC2 (`++ b/.vs/x` tier/file-flip spoof with a `path-warn:.vs/*` allowlist), AC3 (spoofed `++ token:` content scanned in staged AND blob-stdin where the old parser missed it, plus the forged-budget `+@@` probe), AC3b (the zero-byte suppressBlankEmpty context-line exploit, hand-built and real-git), AC4 (the `-- a/x`/`++ b/evil` two-line dance), AC5 (multi-file real-diff byte-identical differential), AC6 (full-history objective-oracle differential with automated spoof-line traceability), AC7 (U3 context lines decrement both, only `+` scanned), AC8 (malformed `@@ -abc,def +xyz @@` + truncated `@@ -5,` fail-safe, no crash/no wedge) — 17/17 green. `shellcheck devcontainer/git-hooks/vibe-content-scan.sh` clean (direct), `python3 code-check.py` clean (15 files), full `python3 smoke-test.py` green (task_022/023 permanent shape + corpus checks intact), `vibe audit --history` ~30s on the vibe repo (under the 60s gate). Scanner header comment documents the hunk-aware contract.
+
 - [x] **task_023: `path-warn:<glob>` allowlist entries — path-scoped WARN suppression so vibe's own repo is self-clean under its own content guard** — after task_019/022, vibe's own tree legitimately contains WARN-class example literals (RFC1918 IPs, example emails, `.local` hostnames) in `smoke-test.py`'s runtime fixtures and `.vs/` harness prose, so a commit touching those files nagged for a `VIBE_CONTENT_GUARD=off` override even though nothing was actually leaking. Global content-allowlisting of the literals was rejected (would blind the guard everywhere); the fix is path-scoped instead. New `.vibe-content-allow` entry kind `path-warn:<glob>` — a bash `case`-style glob (unquoted, so `*` crosses `/`) matched against the repo-relative file path, structurally separate from the file's existing ERE-per-line loop. In `--staged`/`--range` only, `scan_diff_stream` now tracks a per-file `current_file_tier` at each `+++ b/<path>` header: demoted to `block` when the path matches a `path-warn` glob, otherwise left at the mode's tier — a one-way floor (BLOCK rules run unconditionally regardless of tier, so a path can suppress WARN noise but never a secret; `--range` is already block-tier, so path-warn entries are a byte-identical no-op there, pinning the idempotency property). The make-or-break constraint: `path-warn:` lines never reach `line_is_allowlisted`'s `grep -E` loop, in whole-line or stripped-glob form — a glob like `smoke-test.py` fed to ERE would be a live literal-substring suppressor for ANY finding (including BLOCK) on any line merely mentioning the filename, so the parser skips `path-warn:*` lines structurally before that loop ever sees them. New `load_path_warn_globs`/`file_is_path_warn` (lazy-loaded once, no forks, no external commands — bash `case` pattern match only) keep task_022's no-fork hot-path shape intact. Not applied in `--message`/`--messages-stdin`/`--blob-stdin`/`--identity` (no file path exists there; history scans deliberately keep full WARN visibility for the Private→Public flip case). vibe's own `.vibe-content-allow` ships `path-warn:.vs/*` and `path-warn:smoke-test.py`. Documented in `content-guard.md` including the stale-scanner caveat (a pre-task_023 scanner reading a `path-warn:` entry falls back to whole-line ERE matching, so it only suppresses a finding on content containing the literal text `path-warn:smoke-test.py` — narrow, accepted, and the scanner change ships in the same commit as the allowlist entries so vibe's own repo never sits in the mixed state) and the accepted `path-warn:*` (repo-wide WARN-off) degenerate case, same trust model as an already-possible overbroad ERE entry. Verified via a scratch fixture-repo differential harness (not committed — gitignored under `.vs/cycle-*/`) covering AC1 (differential vs `git show HEAD` old scanner, byte-identical with no path-warn entries present), AC2 (staged suppression incl. a 3-levels-deep nested-path case and an empty-glob no-op), AC3/AC3b (BLOCK always fires, staged and range, and path-warn lines proven never to reach the ERE loop via literal-text-collision fixtures), AC3c (`--range` byte-identical with/without path-warn entries), AC4 (`--message`/`--blob-stdin`/`--messages-stdin`/`--identity` byte-identical to the old scanner with path-warn entries present), and AC5 (shipped-entries self-clean end-to-end, both the clean WARN case and a planted-PAT BLOCK case) — 16/16 green. `shellcheck devcontainer/git-hooks/vibe-content-scan.sh` clean (direct invocation — `code-check.py`'s fixture-frozen `scripts()` structurally can't see that directory), `python3 code-check.py` clean (15 files), full `python3 smoke-test.py` green with no regressions (task_022's static no-fork/no-`\b`/no-bash-4 shape guards intact). `vibe audit --history` sanity-timed at ~28s on the vibe repo (well under the 60s gate, no blow-up; task_022's ~22s baseline preserved within normal variance).
 
 - [x] **task_022: `vibe audit --history` performance — fork-storm removal + single-pass message scan** — `vibe audit --history` timed out at 280s on the vibe repo (~230 commits). Two causes, both in the task_019 content guard, both fixed with the finding set held byte-identical (the scanner is a security boundary shared by pre-commit/commit-msg/pre-push and `vibe audit` — a silently-narrowed rule is a shipped hole). (1) **Match primitives (Part A):** the five hot-path functions (`check_rule`, `check_email_rule`, `check_home_path_rule`, `is_named_trailer`, `is_trailer_line`) forked a `printf | grep -oE` (plus a `sed`) per rule per line — ~400k+ subprocesses over `git log -p --all` in pass 1 alone. Swapped to bash-native `[[ =~ ]]` + `BASH_REMATCH`; those bodies now contain zero external-command invocations or command substitutions (a permanent static-shape test guards against the fork-storm returning). Portability held to POSIX ERE for BSD `regcomp` (macOS bash 3.2) and glibc (container bash 5) alike — no bash-4 features, and the `mdns-local` rule's GNU `\b` word-boundary was rewritten to a capture-group POSIX form (`([A-Za-z0-9-]+\.local)([^A-Za-z0-9_]|$)`, snippet taken from group 1 so `foo.localhost` still doesn't match and reported snippets are unchanged). `set -euo pipefail` survival: every match test is guarded in an `if`/`&&`; `nocasematch` is set and restored on every path out of the icase branch (a leak would silently make later case-sensitive rules case-insensitive — an adversarial corpus line with a mixed-case secret trigger and an uppercase `FOO.LOCAL` proves it doesn't). (2) **Single-pass message scan (Part B):** new scanner mode `--messages-stdin` reads NUL-delimited `<sha>\n<body>` records (from `git log --all -z --format='%H%n%B'`), scanning each message line as `commit <sha>` — the NUL delimiter, not line-shape sniffing, is the record boundary, so a body line like `commit deadbeef` or `+foo` is scanned as content and never misparsed; empty/malformed